tionary history of bird diversity, and the evolution of avian reproductive behaviors, plumage ornaments, and social behaviors.In this multifaceted book, Futuyma examines how birds evolved from nonavian dinosaurs and reveals what we can learn from the "family tree" of birds. He looks at the ways natural selection enables different forms of the same species to persist, and discusses how adaptation by natural selection accounts for the diverse life histories of birds and the rich variety of avian parenting styles, mating displays, and cooperative behaviors. He explains why some parts of the planet have so many more species than others, and asks what an evolutionary perspective brings to urgent questions about bird extinction and habitat destruction. Along the way, Futuyma provides an insider's perspective on how biologists practice evolutionary science, from studying the fossil record to comparing DNA sequences among and within species.A must-read for bird enthusiasts and curious naturalists, How Birds Evolve shows how evolutionary biology helps us better understand birds and their natural history, and how the study of birds has informed all aspects of evolutionary science since the time of Darwin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBirdsxEvolution. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Ornithology.2bisacsh  aAccipitriformes.  aAdaptive radiation.  aAllele.  aAllopatric speciation.  aAmino acid.  aBase pair.  aBiologist.  aBird nest.  aBird.  aBrood parasite.  aCalifornia condor.  aCassowary.  aCharacter displacement.  aCharles Darwin.  aCharles Sibley.  aChromosome.  aCnemophilidae.  aCommon cuckoo.  aCommon descent.  aConvergent evolution.  aCoraciiformes.  aCrossbill.  aDarwin's finches.  aDavid Lack.  aDrongo.  aEvolutionary biology.  aExtra-pair copulation.  aFe